       -      FERC's  3rd and 4th quarter plans for 1994.
       -      SCE's "PoolCo" proposal and how it differs from other power pools.

       1993 was largely a year of transition, as FERC moved with
uncharacteristic speed to implement the provisions of the Energy
Policy Act.  In 1994, few were surprised as FERC again shifted gears
and set its sights on restructuring the industry.
       Already we've seen proposals on stranded costs, deregulated
power sales, transmission pricing, and service comparability
standards.
       However, the most significant body of proposed regulation this
year -- or since the passage of the EPAct of 1992 for that matter --
was not issued by Washington, but rather from the California Public
Utilities Commission; the "blue book"on industry deregulation.  While
many industry observers have praised these recent developments in
market deregulation, questions remain about the limits of regulatory
jurisdiction.
       FERC and the states rarely, if ever, have seen eye-to-eye.  But
they now are trying to coordinate the crafting of policies that will
help lead electric utilities into the competitive era.
       In sum, critical issues that unless quickly resolved or, at the
very least, defined, will set the industry's competitive future back
for years, meaning millions of dollars in lost time and investment.
       Over a two day period, The Energy Daily's senior utility
faculty will discuss in great detail their assessments of the current
regulatory climate, innovative industry approaches to the new
competitive regimes, and their visions for how to capitalize on the
new competitive marketplace.
       In many ways, the current period for the electric industry is
similar to 1985 for the gas industry. As they did in the mid-eighties,
industry incumbents are now emphasizing reliability issues,
uncompensated services, new product development and, above all,
protecting market share.
       The Energy Daily's conference, "The Impact of Retail
Competition on the Electric Utility Industry" will explore these
issues through a series of intensive panel discussions and formal
presentations by some of the industry's leading authorities on
deregulation, pricing, new product development and strategic planning.


