                                  MANAGING THE UTILITY IN TIMES OF CHANGE

       This course is designed for utility senior managers who want to explore the requirements imposed by
today's changing utility environment. The seminar will be conducted by Llewellyn King, publisher of "The
Energy Daily" and a recognized expert and long-time lecturer on energy subjects. Attendees will learn how
to capitalize on opportunities and minimize risks.

                     Course Outline for WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 28, 1994, 9:00AM - 5:00PM

Restructuring the Utility
       Many ~gurus~ claim to have the only business plan that will succeed in positioning a utility for
       success today, but the problems defy simplistic solutions.
       - Identifying the core business.
       - What determines which units are worth saving.
       - Which keepers are compatible with the core business.
       - Advantages and drawbacks in ~hiving off~ units.
       - What lessons can we learn from deregulated
          industries.

The Media and Utilities
       Dealing with the media is the most important element of a utility~s public image.
       - How the media works and what drives it.
       - How to make friends with the local media.
       - How to get the maximum out of the news you generate.
       - What are the most important things to do in a crisis.

LUNCHEON:  Management Roundtable Discussions
       - Find out what the others are doing.
       - What works and what doesn~t.
       - How have others reacted to your problems.

Risk Management for Utilities
       It is too late to worry about risk after the damage is done. Utilities must look at their risk equations
       and plan for contingencies.
       - The consequences of technological risks.
       - Public policy as the greatest potential risk.
       - Doing your political homework.
       - Educating the public and the PUCs.


The Utility "Hot Buttons" for 1995 and Beyond
       Utilities will survive if they position themselves to deal with the major issues and to take advantage
       of opportunities in the new utility environment.
       - EMF: The reality vs. the public perception
       - Driving diversification in new generation.
       - Converting rate payer into customers.
       - What "the customer is always right" means to a utility.
       - How new technology will develop as utilities break up.
       - Biting the bullet on stranded investment.
       - The role of futures and derivatives in utility finances.
       - Opportunities in common carrier access.



ABOUT THE SPEAKER*****
Llewellyn King was born in Southern Rhodesia, now Zimbabwe, and has been a journalist since 1956.  He
has worked for major newspapers in London, New York and Washington.  He was educated at Churchill
College before embarking on a career in journalism.

In 1973, he launched the nation's premier energy industry newsletter, The Energy Daily, and currently
publishes ten specialized trade journals.  He has appeared on major American television programs including
the "Today Show," "Meet the Press," "WorldNet" and most recently as guest commentator on "The Nightly
Business Report," and the "MacNeil Lehrer News Hour" as well as having been published in hundreds of
newspapers and magazines around the world, including the Financial Times, The Times of India and the
Journal of Commerce.


